{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0ed05a7e-b6a0-4951-96ac-771ba0f3e823","content":"The .NET MAUI Android build system **doesn't reliably use `JAVA_HOME`**. It has its own JDK resolution logic (MSBuild's `JavaSdkDirectory`) and often ignores the environment variable entirely.\n\n**Fix — pick one:**\n\n**Option A (Recommended):** Let the .NET workload install & manage its own JDK:\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui-android\n```\nThis installs the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK in a location the build system finds automatically.\n\n**Option B:** Explicitly point MSBuild to your Temurin JDK. Add to your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\nOr pass it on the command line:\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\nVerify the actual path with:\n```bash\n/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cdda86ec-9e68-41c9-9599-2ff5daa7ff77","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android + Java issues:\n\n1. .NET MAUI Android builds require a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI/Android workloads ship with their own JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK 17), and the build system looks for it in a specific location.\n\n2. A common issue is that the build uses `JavaSdkDirectory` which may not match `JAVA_HOME`. \n\nThe Android build tasks search for the JDK in a specific order, and .NET 9+ (along with recent .NET 8 versions) requires JDK 17. The real problem on macOS with Adoptium Temurin is likely the installation path—Adoptium installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, but .NET MAUI's Android build tasks are specifically looking for the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution that gets installed with the Android workload.\n\nWithout seeing the exact error message, I'm considering the most common culprits: the build can't locate the JDK at all, there's a version parsing issue, the JDK version is incompatible with the build tools, or there's a problem with the `dx` tool.\n\nOn macOS specifically, Adoptium Temurin installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, but the .NET Android SDK might not be checking that location or respecting the `JAVA_HOME` environment variable. More likely though, since .NET 8, the Android workload installs its own Microsoft Build of OpenJDK and prefers that over any system `JAVA_HOME` setting. If that workload JDK is missing or corrupted, the build fails regardless of what `JAVA_HOME` points to. The solution usually involves reinstalling the workload or explicitly configuring the JDK path in the project. I'm realizing the core issue is likely how macOS resolves the JDK path—the .NET Android build tools check specific locations in a particular order, starting with the `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property, then falling back to the workload-installed JDK, and finally checking environment variables. Since Temurin installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home` on macOS, the build system might not be finding it automatically.\n\nThe solution is to explicitly set the JDK path either in the project file or via the command line when building, which bypasses the fallback chain and points directly to the Temurin installation.","outputTokens":1632,"requestId":"110E:19B167:C10F9E:E14B26:69FE8588"},"id":"d50586f8-2a9a-4d0b-9520-0ce47dba6ffa","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:54:00.015Z","parentId":"a500595a-6894-4e16-80e6-7b11526ef36d"}
